## Appendix A Joint Inference with SG-MCMC

In this section, we propose an alternative formulation that enables a joint inference framework for \(\bm{p},\bm{W},\bm{\Theta}\) using SG-MCMC, thereby avoiding the need for variational inference for \(\bm{W}\).

We adopt a continuous relaxation of \(\bm{W}\), similar to [43], by introducing a latent variable \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\). The graphical model is illustrated in Figure 5. We can define

\[p(\bm{W}|\tilde{\bm{W}})=\prod_{i,j}p(W_{ij}|\tilde{W}_{ij})\] (16)

with \(p(W_{ij}=1|\tilde{W}_{ij})=\sigma(\tilde{W}_{ij})\) where \(\sigma(\cdot)\) is the sigmoid function. In other words, \(\tilde{W}ij\) defines the existence logits of \(Wij\).

With the introduction of \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\), the original posterior expectations of \(p(\bm{p},\bm{W},\bm{\Theta}|\bm{D})\), e.g. during evaluation, can be translated using the following proposition.

**Proposition A.1** (Equivalence of posterior expectation).: _Under the generative model Figure 5, we have_

\[\mathbb{E}_{p(\bm{p},\bm{W},\bm{\Theta}|\bm{D})}\left[\bm{f}(\bm{G}=\tau(\bm{ p},\bm{W}),\bm{\Theta})\right]=\mathbb{E}_{p(\bm{p},\tilde{\bm{W}},\bm{\Theta})} \left[\frac{\mathbb{E}_{p(\bm{W}|\tilde{\bm{W}})}\left[f(\bm{G},\bm{\Theta})p( \bm{D},\bm{\Theta}|\bm{p},\bm{W})\right]}{\mathbb{E}_{p(\bm{W}|\tilde{\bm{W}} )}\left[p(\bm{D},\bm{\Theta}|\bm{p},\bm{W})\right]}\right]\] (17)

_where \(\bm{f}\) is the target quantity._

This proof is in Appendix B.3.

With this proposition, instead of sampling \(\bm{W}\), use SG-MCMC to draw \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\) samples. Similar to Section 4.2, to use SG-MCMC for \(\bm{p},\tilde{\bm{W}},\bm{\Theta}\), we need their gradient information. The following proposition specifies the required gradients.

**Proposition A.2**.: _With the generative model defined as Figure 5, we have_

\[\nabla_{\bm{p},\bm{\Theta},\tilde{\bm{W}}}U(\bm{p},\tilde{\bm{W} },\bm{\Theta})= -\nabla_{\bm{p}}\log p(\bm{p})-\nabla_{\bm{\Theta}}\log p(\bm{ \Theta})\] \[-\nabla_{\tilde{\bm{W}}}\log p(\tilde{\bm{W}})-\nabla_{\bm{p}, \bm{\Theta},\tilde{\bm{W}}}\log\mathbb{E}_{p(\bm{W}|\tilde{\bm{W}})}[p(\bm{D} |\bm{W},\bm{p},\bm{\Theta})]\] (18)

The proof is in Appendix B.4.

With these gradients, we can directly plug in existing SG-MCMC samplers to draw samples for \(\bm{p},\tilde{\bm{W}}\), and \(\bm{\Theta}\) in joint inference (Algorithm 2).

