### Proof of Theorem 3.1

For completeness, we recite the theorem here.

_Theorem 3.1_ (Equivalence of inference in \((\bm{W},\bm{p})\) and binary DAG space).: Assume graph \(\bm{G}\) is a binary adjacency matrix representing a DAG and node potential \(\bm{p}\) does not contain the same values, i.e. \(p_{i}\neq p_{j}\ \forall i,j\). Then, with the induced joint observational distribution \(p(\bm{D},\bm{G})\), dataset \(\bm{D}\) and a corresponding prior \(p(\bm{G})\), we have

\[p(\bm{G}|\bm{D})=\int p_{\tau}(\bm{p},\bm{W}|\bm{D})\,\mathbb{1}(\bm{G}=\tau( \bm{W},\bm{p}))d\bm{W}d\bm{p}\] (19)

if \(p(\bm{G})=\int p_{\tau}(\bm{p},\bm{W})\,\mathbb{1}(\bm{G}=\tau(\bm{W},\bm{p})) d\bm{W}d\bm{p}\), where \(p_{\tau}(\bm{W},\bm{p})\) is the prior, \(\mathbb{1}(\cdot)\) is the indicator function and \(p_{\tau}(\bm{p},\bm{W}|D)\) is the posterior distribution over \(\bm{p},\bm{W}\).

