To prove this theorem, we first prove the following lemma stating the equivalence of \(\tau\) (Equation (5)) to binary DAG space.

**Lemma B.1** (Equivalence of \(\tau\) to DAG space).: _Consider \(d\) random variables, a node potential vector \(\bm{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\) and a binary matrix \(\bm{W}\in\{0,1\}^{d\times d}\). Then the following holds:_

1. _For any_ \(\bm{W}\in\{0,1\}^{d\times d}\)_,_ \(\bm{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\)_,_ \(\bm{G}=\tau(\bm{W},\bm{p})\) _is a DAG._
2. _For any DAG_ \(\bm{G}\in\mathbb{D}\)_, where_ \(\mathbb{D}\) _is the space of all DAGs, there exists a corresponding_ \((\bm{W},\bm{p})\) _such that_ \(\tau(\bm{W},\bm{p})=\bm{G}\)_._

Proof.: The main proof directly follows the theorem 2.1 in [72]. For (a), we show the output from \(\tau(\bm{W},\bm{p})\) must be a DAG. By leveraging the Lemma 3.4 in [72], we can easily obtain that \(\mathrm{Step}(\mathrm{grad}\,\bm{p})\) emits a binary adjacency matrix representing a DAG. The only difference is that we replace the \(\mathrm{ReLU}(\cdot)\) with \(\mathrm{Step}(\cdot)\) but the conclusion can be directly generalized.

For (b), we show that for any DAG \(\bm{G}\), there exists a \((\bm{W},\bm{p})\) pair s.t. \(\tau(\bm{W},\bm{p})=\bm{G}\). To see this, we can observe that \(\bm{p}\) implicitly defines a topological order in the mapping \(\tau\). For any \(p_{i}>p_{j}\), we have \(j\to i\) after the mapping \(\mathrm{Step}(\mathrm{grad}\,\bm{p})\). Thus, by leveraging Theorem 3.7 in [72], we obtain that there exists a potential vector \(\bm{p}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\) for any DAG \(\bm{G}\) such that

\[(\mathrm{grad}\,\bm{p})(i,j)>0\quad\text{ when }G_{ij}=1\]

Thus, we can choose \(\bm{W}\) in the following way:

\[\bm{W}=\left\{\begin{array}{rl}&W_{ij}=0\quad\text{ if }G_{ij}=0\\ &W_{ij}=1\quad\text{ if }G_{ij}=1\end{array}\right.\]

Next, let's prove the Theorem 3.1.

Proof of Theorem 3.1.: From Lemma B.1, we see that the mapping is complete. Namely, the \((\bm{W},\bm{p})\) space can represent the entire DAG space. Next, we show that performing Bayesian inference in \((\bm{W},\bm{p})\) space can also correspond to the inference in DAG space.

