### Performance of SG-MCMC with Continuous Relaxation

We compare the performance of SG-MCMC+VI and SG-MCMC with \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\) on \(d=10\) ER and SF graph settings. Figure 9 shows the performance comparison. We can observe that SG-MCMC+VI generally outperforms its counterpart in most of the metrics. We hypothesize that this is because VI network \(\mu_{\phi}\) couples \(\bm{p}\) and \(\bm{W}\). This coupling effect is crucial since the changes in \(\bm{p}\) results in the change of permutation matrix, where the \(\bm{W}\) can immediately respond to this change through \(\mu_{\phi}\). On the other hand, \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\) can only respond to this change through running SG-MCMC steps on \(\tilde{\bm{W}}\) with fixed \(\bm{p}\). In theory, this is the most flexible approach since this coupling do not requires parametric form like \(\mu_{\phi}\). However in practice, we cannot run many SG-MCMC steps with fixed \(\bm{p}\) for convergence, which results in the inferior performance.

